Lake Elementary PTO
April 2, 2019 at 7:21 AM ¬∑

Have you heard about The Glider Pack Program? The Glider Pack Program is a joint venture of Lake Local Schools and community partners to provide supplemental food for children in our community with household food insecurities. This program is for children currently attending Lake Local Schools and children under school age in the household.
For the households showing the need, our goal is to send home supplemental food on Fridays for the weekend for the children in that household.
We are working towards what we can do to help our community children outside of school, as well as in school, and the Glider Pack Program is one way to do this.

We‚Äôd like to assist the program coordinator by stocking the pantry shelves! If you bring a donation of protein(peanut butter, canned chicken, canned tuna or canned meat) to Carnival we‚Äôll give you a free raffle ticket for the Basket Raffle that will be drawn Friday night! Let‚Äôs show them how the Elementary can stock the shelves!!

post_text:
With today being Fee Day I‚Äôm sure everyone is very excited to find out which teacher their child will have this year. Please remember to be courteous with your comments on Social Media or actually any time. Our teachers invest many, many hours of their time to give your child the best education and grade level experience they can.

Enjoy your final weeks of summer!
shared_text:
Napoleon Elementary School PTO
August 9, 2017 at 11:07 AM ¬∑

Shared by a friend and I thought it was worth spreading. ‚ù§Ô∏è

Quick back-to-school reminder When you receive your child's teacher assignment in the next few weeks, be kind and remember that social media spreads far and wide. Even the simple question of "Does anyone know anything about Mr/s. So-and-so?" can lead to a firestorm of opinions that may not all be positive. Remember, someone else's experience won't necessarily be yours. Teachers come in all different packages and personalities, just like all parents and students. I'm sure you wouldn't want the teachers asking all our cyber friends what they know about your child as a student or you as a parent, and using those opinions to determine how the year will go. Extend the same courtesy to your child's teacher, get to know him/her, ask questions, and give him/her a chance. You may find that the teacher you heard was __________, was exactly what your kiddo needed.

Happy Last Weeks of Summer!

SHPBEDS.ORG
Request a Free Bed

The Press Newspapers
July 18, 2018 at 10:02 AM ¬∑

The Maumee Valley chapter of Sleep in Heavenly Peace (SHP) is taking applications for beds.

Children between age 3 and 17 who do not have a bed and live in Northwest Ohio are eligible to receive a free bed, complete with mattress, sheets, comforter, and pillow. You can request beds for your family or you can refer someone who you know that needs a bed. Requests must be made on the website: https://www.shpbeds.org/request-bed

SHP is a non-profit 501¬©3 relying on donations for funding and all beds are built by volunteers on ‚ÄúBuild Days‚Äù. Their first build day will be July 21 from 9 a.m.-noon at the Whitehouse Campus of CedarCreek Church. As part of their inaugural ServeDay, Groups from CedarCreek have chosen to sponsor and volunteer to build beds for SHP ‚Äì Maumee Valley. Although this first build is fully staffed, interested parties can contact SHP through Facebook to receive information on sponsoring or participating in upcoming builds: https://www.facebook.com/SHPMaumeeValley/

shared_text:
THEDENVERCHANNEL.COM
One school's getting-to-know-you approach to preventing a school shooting

Flyer Flight Crew
May 25, 2018 at 1:01 PM ¬∑

National school safety expert Amy Klinger, of Educator's School Safety Network, was asked by reporter Chris Welch with Scripps News Network out of Denver, for examples of schools being proactive in school safety. Lake Local Schools was one of the two examples (Licking Valley being the other) in the state of Ohio she shared as schools being proactive and on right path. On Tuesday May 22nd Chris visited our campus to observe our morning routine and our approach to school safety.

Each one of our staff members should be commended for consistently working towards keeping our students and buildings a safe place.

https://www.thedenverchannel.com/the-now/one-schools-getting-to-know-you-approach-to-preventing-a-school-shooting

On Tuesday May 22nd Chris visited our campus to observe our morning routine and our approach to school safety.

Each one of our staff members should be commended for consistently working towards keeping our students and buildings a safe place.

https://www.thedenverchannel.com/the-now/one-schools-getting-to-know-you-approach-to-preventing-a-school-shooting

Meet Mila Simpkins - one of our preschoolers in Miss Pfister‚Äôs class. Mila has CDLS - Cornelia De Lang Syndrome, a developmental disorder that affects many parts of the body. The features of this disorder vary widely among affected individuals and range from relatively mild to severe.
Cornelia de Lange syndrome is characterized by slow growth before and after birth leading to short stature; intellectual disability that is usually moderate to severe; and abnormalities of bones in the arms, hands, and fingers. Most people with Cornelia de Lange syndrome also have distinctive facial features, including arched eyebrows that often meet in the middle (synophrys), long eyelashes, low-set ears,‚Ä¶ More

‚ÄúTaco Bout Awesome‚Äù! We have the most awesome teachers, administration and staff at Lake Elementary! The PTO wanted to give them a little treat today to kickoff Teacher Appreciation Week and show our appreciation for all they do for all of us on a daily basis. It‚Äôs not an easy job, not an 8:45 to 3:15 kind of job. These ladies and gents work tirelessly for our kiddos all the time. Have you ever driven by school after hours, on the weekends or even Holiday breaks? You most definitely saw at least one car in the parking lot. Grading papers, prepping for the next week or rearranging their classroom for something new and exciting to keep our kiddo‚Äôs engaged. We truly are blessed to have these teachers in our children‚Äôs lives.

Thank you from the Lake Elementary PTO, we truly appreciate you!

The Glider Pack Program is a joint venture of Lake Local Schools and community partners to provide supplemental food for children in our community with household food insecurities. This program is for children currently attending Lake Local Schools and children under school age in the household.

We are in need of non-perishable items to stock our pantry.

This Friday, January 19, 2018 at our home Boys Basketball game against Otsego we will be having the GLIDER PACK "Box Out". We are asking for donations of canned or boxed entrees such as soup, ravioli and macaroni & cheese (or any non perishable items) to be dropped off at our GLIDER PACK collection table in the Runway at Lake High School.

On February 9, 2018 at our home Boys Basketball game against Elmwood we will have the "PROTEIN PASS" and are asking for jars of peanut butter, canned meat or cheese sauce (or any non perishable items). Simply drop off your donation at the GLIDER PACK collection table in the Runway at Lake High School. If you have any questions please feel free to contact Chris Wilson cwilson@lakeschools.org

post_text: With permission from Napoleon Elementary PTO, I thought I'd share this! This speaks volumes in more ways than one!
shared_text:
Napoleon Elementary School PTO
August 9, 2017 at 11:07 AM ¬∑

Shared by a friend and I thought it was worth spreading. ‚ù§Ô∏è

Quick back-to-school reminder When you receive your child's teacher assignment in the next few weeks, be kind and remember that social media spreads far and wide. Even the simple question of "Does anyone know anything about Mr/s. So-and-so?" can lead to a firestorm of opinions that may not all be positive. Remember, someone else's experience won't necessarily be yours. Teachers come in all different packages and personalities, just like all parents and students. I'm sure you wouldn't want the teachers asking all our cyber friends what they know about your child as a student or you as a parent, and using those opinions to determine how the year will go. Extend the same courtesy to your child's teacher, get to know him/her, ask questions, and give him/her a chance. You may find that the teacher you heard was __________, was exactly what your kiddo needed.

Happy Last Weeks of Summer!
